\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A finite group with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements can be characterized by its multiplication table.
 Construct a square 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-by-
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 table, writing the product 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}g_{j}$
\end_inset

 in the square in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th row and the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

th column.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because of the group properties, in each row any element can appear once
 and only once, otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}g_{j}=g_{i}g_{k}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq k$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplying with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 from the left yields 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{j}=g_{k}$
\end_inset

, which contradicts our assumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, each element of the group appear only once in each row or column of
 the table.
 This is called the 
\series bold
once and only once rule
\end_layout

